  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal. **Money laundering** is the process of making illegally obtained funds (often from crimes such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear to be legitimate by passing them through a complex sequence of financial transactions. Its purpose is to disguise the illegal origin of the money so it can be used without detection by law enforcement.\n\nMoney laundering is prohibited by law in virtually every country, and it is typically prosecuted as a serious criminal offense. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, imprisonment, asset forfeiture, and other legal consequences. Governments and international organizations, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, work to combat money laundering through regulations, oversight, and enforcement.\n\nFinancial institutions and businesses are also required to implement **anti-money laundering (AML)** measures to detect and report suspicious activities. Failure to comply with these regulations can result in severe penalties for both individuals and organizations.",
